## 📖 Overview

Sports turf booking needs to feel instant — no one wants to wait on a spinner to find a nearby venue. This project pushes both **compute** (edge deployment) and **correctness** (business logic) as close to the data as possible: the UI runs at the edge for speed, and PostgreSQL itself enforces the rules that must never be broken.

## ✨ Key Features

- 🗺️ **Interactive map-based discovery** using Leaflet — find and book nearby turfs visually
- ⚡ **Edge deployment** for low-latency access regardless of user location
- 🛡️ **PL/pgSQL triggers & functions** enforce critical business rules (e.g. no overlapping bookings) directly at the database layer, so consistency doesn't depend on the application code getting it right every time
- 🧭 Built with **React 19** and **TanStack Start** for a fast, modern data-fetching experience

## 🏗️ Architecture

```
┌───────────────────────┐
│   React 19 + TanStack   │
│   Start (Edge-deployed)  │
└───────────┬─────────────┘
            │
            ▼
     ┌──────────────┐
     │   Supabase    │
     │  (Auth + API)  │
     └───────┬──────┘
            ▼
     ┌──────────────────────┐
     │      PostgreSQL         │
     │  PL/pgSQL triggers &     │
     │  functions enforce        │
     │  booking consistency       │
     └──────────────────────┘
```

## 🧰 Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|---|---|
| Frontend | React 19, TanStack Start |
| Maps | Leaflet |
| Backend / Auth | Supabase |
| Database | PostgreSQL (PL/pgSQL) |

## 🚀 Getting Started

```bash
git clone https://github.com/hackerstudent29/Formora.git
cd Formora

npm install
npm run dev
```

Set your Supabase project URL and anon key in `.env`:
```
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=your_project_url
VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your_anon_key
```

